Implications for Evaluation Design
For evaluation terms of reference, the relationship can be expressed as follows:

The evaluation will use the OECD DAC criteria as the main evaluative lenses and a Value for Investment approach to synthesise evidence into an overall judgement about whether the resources invested were justified by the value created.

This wording avoids two common problems. It avoids reducing VfI to the DAC efficiency criterion. It also avoids treating the DAC criteria as a checklist that automatically produces a value judgement.
The design should then specify:

which DAC criteria will be used and why;
whether any criteria need to be adapted, combined, or deprioritised;
what additional VfI criteria are needed for the context;
what standards define poor, adequate, good, or excellent performance;
what evidence will be used for each criterion;
how evidence will be synthesised into an overall judgement.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

pilot or test plan;
user needs evidence;
test-and-learn design;
proof-of-concept findings;
pilot evaluation report;
decision log showing changes made because of testing;
procurement strategy reflecting staged commitment;
financial model showing pilot and scale-up costs;
lessons learned and risk updates.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

should-cost model and model specification;
book of assumptions and data log;
development checklist and quality assurance plan;
sensitivity analysis and scenario outputs;
comparison of should-cost estimate with bids;
records of model governance and review;
documented use of model outputs in delivery model assessment, business case, evaluation, negotiation, or contract management.

Purpose and Scope
The playbook applies to service delivery choices across outsourcing, insourcing, mixed economy approaches, and contracting. It is aimed at commercial, procurement, finance, project delivery, policy, legal, digital, and operational colleagues involved in public service delivery decisions.
For VfM rubric creation, the source is useful because it identifies what government treats as material to good sourcing:

the health and capability of the market;
early engagement and transparency;
evidence-based delivery model assessment;
should-cost modelling and whole-life cost understanding;
testing and piloting before committing to scale;
clear specifications, KPIs, baselines, and evaluation criteria;
risk allocation, pricing, supplier financial standing, and resolution planning;
contract management and strategic supplier relationship management.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

commercial pipeline entries and market engagement records;
market health and capability assessments;
project validation review outputs;
delivery model assessment records;
should-cost models, assumptions logs, and quality assurance records;
pilot or test-and-learn evidence;
service specifications, KPI baselines, and performance measures;
bid evaluation model and evaluation report;
risk allocation matrix, pricing model, and payment mechanism;
supplier economic and financial standing assessment;
resolution plan and continuity arrangements;
contract management and benefits reporting records.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

framework provider customer guidance;
framework-level market health and capability assessment;
call-off market and delivery model assessment;
rationale for using the framework route;
call-off competition records and evaluation report;
framework pricing information and benchmark evidence;
criticality assessment for the call-off;
supplier economic and financial standing checks where relevant.

One-Page Summary
The sourcing and consultancy playbooks are relevant to VfM rubric creation because they define what good commercial preparation, market engagement, delivery model choice, bid evaluation, risk allocation, benefits monitoring, and knowledge transfer should look like in public sector sourcing.
They should not be used as a checklist where every procedural step becomes a rubric criterion. They should be used selectively where they help define good resource use, relevant evidence, explicit standards, and trade-offs.
The main rubric contribution is a stronger bridge between commercial practice and evaluative judgement:

sourcing choices define the alternatives and cost side of VfM;
market and supplier evidence define economy, fairness, and resilience;
bid evaluation evidence defines how price, quality, social value, and deliverability were weighed;
risk allocation and pricing evidence define whether the contract is sustainable;
benefits and knowledge transfer evidence define whether value is realised after award.

Candidate Evidence Checklist
For generic public-sector VfM rubric creation, consider whether the evidence base includes:

value proposition and theory of change;
business case and options appraisal;
delivery model assessment;
market health and capability assessment;
should-cost model and assumptions;
pilot or testing evidence where uncertainty is material;
specification, KPIs, baselines, and quality criteria;
bid evaluation report;
social value and fairness evidence where relevant;
risk allocation matrix, pricing model, and payment mechanism;
supplier financial standing and continuity evidence;
benefits register and benefits reports;
knowledge generation and transfer evidence for consultancy.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

business case benefits register;
categorisation of commercial benefits;
KPI definitions and measurement plan;
baseline, target, and actual performance data;
12-month benefits review record;
annual benefits reports;
supplier consultation evidence where used;
SRO and commercial lead review records;
external review reports for complex outsourcing samples.

Relationship to Evaluation
The indicator creates a portfolio-level evaluation opportunity. Evaluators can use it to identify which approved projects were expected to deliver strong VfM, then investigate:

whether the original categories were robust;
whether schemes delivered the benefits and costs assumed at approval;
whether lower or higher realised value was driven by delivery, demand, price, scope, or external-context changes;
whether non-monetised impacts strengthened or weakened achieved value;
whether lessons should change future TAG assumptions or DfT category judgements.

This is where the Magenta Book VfM Evaluation and OPM King VfM Guidance can add value. They provide methods for judging actual value when the evidence is mixed and not all effects can be monetised.

Practical Implications
For the knowledge base, the DfT indicator should be coded as an appraisal transparency source rather than an evaluation source.
Useful note fields include:

reporting year and project scope;
spending included and excluded;
category distribution by approved spending;
stated limitations and uncertainty;
any explicit caveats about expected versus achieved value;
links back to the DfT VfM Framework.

This prevents a common mistake: treating an ex ante portfolio indicator as proof of ex post performance.

Lessons for VfM Evaluation
The two examples illustrate several recurring issues:

portfolio VfM can hide variation between schemes;
aggregate BCRs depend on consistent methods and comparable assumptions;
small schemes may lack strong monitoring and evaluation data;
non-monetised impacts can be important even when the headline result is monetised;
sensitivity tests are essential when evidence is partial;
expected value should not be confused with achieved value.

These lessons connect the examples to the DfT VfM Indicator, which also reports expected value at approval rather than evaluated value after delivery.

Practical Implications
For future transport VfM notes, case examples should record:

funding stream and scheme population;
whether evidence is ex ante, in-flight, or ex post;
monetised benefits and costs included in the aggregate figure;
non-monetised impacts handled outside the aggregate figure;
quality of monitoring and evaluation evidence;
sensitivity tests and assumptions;
implications for future appraisal and evaluation design.

This makes the examples useful not just as reported results, but as evidence about how transport VfM assessment works in practice.

Appraisal Scope
TAG covers several linked areas:

overview material on the transport appraisal process;
guidance for senior responsible officers and technical project managers;
appraisal units on cost-benefit analysis, costs, user and provider impacts, economic impacts, environmental impacts, social impacts, distributional impacts, and mode-specific issues;
modelling guidance on forecasting, demand modelling, assignment, calibration, validation, and uncertainty;
appraisal worksheets, databooks, software tools, supplementary guidance, and update reports.

The scope shows why transport VfM is broader than transport user benefits alone. A credible appraisal needs to account for economic, environmental, social, place-based, distributional, and uncertainty evidence where material.

Practical Implications
When integrating TAG into a VfM evidence base, useful notes should separate:

appraisal methods used to forecast value;
modelling assumptions and TAG databook values;
non-monetised effects and how they were described;
sensitivity and uncertainty analysis;
monitoring and evaluation plans;
evidence gaps that later evaluation should close.

This makes TAG useful both as a source of appraisal standards and as a map of claims that can be tested after transport interventions are delivered.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

decision record explaining the knowledge or skills gap;
delivery model assessment or alternatives analysis;
consultancy business case and approval record;
specification and statement of outcomes;
evaluation criteria and bid evaluation report;
pricing and payment mechanism;
spend data capture;
client-side resourcing plan;
deliverable acceptance records;
knowledge generation and transfer plan;
reuse evidence, capability-building evidence, and lessons learned.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

knowledge and skills transfer plan;
statement of expected knowledge products or skills outcomes;
procurement and controls assessment of knowledge transfer;
contract clauses or deliverables covering transfer and sharing;
training, coaching, shadowing, or community-of-practice evidence;
knowledge assets uploaded or shared through appropriate platforms;
internal staff feedback on capability gained;
reuse evidence after the assignment;
exit and handover records.

Practical Implications for Defence VfM Evaluation
For future defence cases, the note suggests recording:

the original strategic rationale, including alliance commitments and national objectives;
the theory of change from capability delivery to military effects and societal value;
operational efficiency evidence on cost, schedule, quality, and readiness;
tactical effectiveness evidence from users, exercises, deployments, and operational demand;
strategic relevance evidence linked to future force structure and threat context;
dependencies on other capabilities, personnel, budgets, doctrine, and allies;
wider positive and negative impacts, including learning from procurement and implementation;
whether monetised analysis is feasible, and how non-monetised defence value will be judged.

The Maud example is especially useful because it resists a simple pass/fail conclusion. It shows that a defence acquisition may be operationally troubled, tactically useful, and strategically contingent at the same time.

Practical Implications
For evaluators taking notes from a transport business case, the useful extraction fields are:

stage of business case and investment decision point;
strategic objectives and spending objectives;
preferred option and alternatives rejected;
VfM category, BCR, net present value, and non-monetised impacts;
key risks, sensitivities, optimism bias, and uncertainty analysis;
distributional and place-based claims;
benefits management, monitoring, and evaluation commitments.

These fields make it possible to connect DfT appraisal evidence to later process, impact, and value for money evaluation.

Risk and Uncertainty
The framework places weight on uncertainty because transport benefits and costs often depend on long-term demand, delivery risk, behavioural response, technology change, environmental assumptions, and wider economic conditions.
Good VfM advice should therefore show:

central estimates and the assumptions behind them;
sensitivity tests around material drivers of benefits and costs;
switching values where useful for showing what would need to change to alter the category;
optimism bias, cost risk, and delivery risk where relevant;
the direction and scale of non-monetised effects.

The practical implication is that uncertainty is part of the VfM judgement, not a caveat added after the result.

VFI Relevance
JSP 507 is strongest where a defence VfI assessment needs defensible appraisal and evaluation evidence. It is especially relevant to:

identifying credible options and comparators;
building whole-life cost evidence;
distinguishing relevant costs from sunk costs, transfer payments, common costs, hidden costs, and double counting;
using cost-effectiveness analysis where benefits cannot be monetised credibly;
presenting COEIA-style comparisons of operational or business effectiveness against through-life costs;
handling infrastructure, personnel, operating, and private-sector costs;
testing affordability alongside value;
treating optimism bias, risk, and uncertainty explicitly;
planning evaluation before implementation and using outturn evidence after implementation;
creating an audit trail for business-case scrutiny, assurance, and later learning.

This makes JSP 507 highly relevant to VFI criteria, subcriteria, standards, and evidence planning, but mainly as source material. It should not be copied mechanically into a rubric. A defence VfI framework still needs to decide which criteria matter, what good performance means in context, which trade-offs are acceptable, and how monetised and non-monetised evidence will be synthesised.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

evaluation strategy and timetable;
award criteria and weightings;
price, quality, social value, and deliverability scoring model;
rationale for weighting choices;
test outputs for the evaluation model;
published procurement documents;
evaluator training and conflict records;
moderation and consensus scoring records;
low-cost bid clarification or referral records;
final evaluation report and bidder feedback.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

service definition and technical specification;
list of feasible delivery options and screening rationale;
strategic and operational criteria with weightings;
evidence base for each option;
should-cost model and assumptions;
sensitivity testing of criteria weights and costs;
market evidence;
in-house capability evidence;
transition and implementation risk assessment;
documented recommendation and approval trail.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

market health and capability assessment;
commercial pipeline and early market engagement evidence;
supplier concentration and contestability analysis;
switching and exit analysis;
evidence on barriers to entry or expansion;
strategic outline business case market section;
commercial strategy choices responding to market weaknesses;
records of supplier feedback and market testing.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

risk register and risk allocation matrix;
commercial strategy risk analysis;
pricing model and payment mechanism;
inflation and indexation rationale;
supplier pricing assumptions;
onerous contract review or root cause analysis where applicable;
contract change records;
risk monitoring reports;
performance and payment data.

Evidence Useful for Rubric Creation
Candidate evidence:

contract criticality assessment;
economic and financial standing assessment;
financial viability and risk assessment tool outputs where used;
bidder clarifications and mitigation proposals;
guarantees, bonds, parent company support, or other mitigations;
ongoing monitoring plan;
key supplier monitoring records;
financial distress event records;
annual confirmation of compliance;
continuity and resolution planning evidence.

This report provides practical guidance for generating Value for Investment (VfI) rubrics for defence programmes. It is not official policy. It is a design guide for evaluators who need to create defensible criteria, subcriteria, performance standards, and evidence plans before judging value for money.
The report complements the Defence VfM Guidance report. That report explains how to apply a rubric-based VfM evaluation in defence. This report focuses one step earlier: how to build the rubric architecture itself.
The method is grounded in Oxford Policy Management’s approach to VfM assessment and Verian’s Value for Investment guidance (King et al. 2023; King and Hurrell 2024). Those sources provide the core judgement discipline: understand the programme, define the value proposition, select criteria, write standards, identify evidence, analyse mixed evidence, and synthesise a transparent overall judgement.
Additional defence and UK government sources help populate the rubric:

the Green Book provides objectives, social value, option comparison, monetised and unmonetised effects, distribution, risk, and uncertainty (HM Treasury 2026, 2022);
JSP 507 provides MOD appraisal and evaluation evidence on requirements, options, whole-life cost, cost-effectiveness analysis, Combined Operational Effectiveness and Investment Appraisal, risk, optimism bias, affordability, and outturn evaluation (Ministry of Defence 2014a, 2014b);
the Sourcing Playbook and related sourcing guidance provide commercial evidence on delivery model choice, market health, should-cost modelling, bid evaluation, risk allocation, benefits, and supplier resilience (Cabinet Office and Government Commercial Function 2026);
the Government Efficiency Framework provides tests for efficiency claims, savings validity, baselines, netting, recurrence, assurance, and protection of outputs and outcomes (HM Treasury 2025a, 2025b).

Use this report when a defence evaluation needs a tailored rubric rather than a generic checklist. It is most useful for capability acquisition, digital and cyber programmes, infrastructure, support and logistics, personnel programmes, commercial service delivery, consultancy, and transformation activity.

